{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ca7e5215-1351-4234-a891-be3d98680179","content":"CLR activation logs are **not the right tool** for diagnosing a `NullReferenceException`. Here's why:\n\n- **CLR activation logs** diagnose runtime *loading* issues — e.g., wrong CLR version selected, runtime fails to load, or unexpected .NET 3.5 dialogs.\n- A **NullReferenceException** is a managed code bug (dereferencing `null`), which happens *after* the runtime has already loaded successfully.\n\n**To diagnose your NullReferenceException, you should instead:**\n\n1. Check the exception stack trace (it tells you exactly which line hit `null`)\n2. Use a debugger (`dotnet run` with breakpoints, or attach with VS/VS Code)\n3. Enable first-chance exception logging\n4. Collect a crash dump (`dotnet-dump collect`)\n\nWould you like help with any of these approaches? If you can share the stack trace or exception details, I can help pinpoint the bug.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"23d384b6-2601-4f00-8eef-fe0150b77e70","outputTokens":224,"requestId":"5023:2C79E8:21D543:29A88A:69F55146"},"id":"40269a05-d35a-4282-a956-c4c3bb0408e1","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:20:17.062Z","parentId":"fde6ec96-dfaf-4de9-a34c-8c0c1c247d34"}
